My relationship with creativity is very similar to my relationship with mindfulness. 

I see it as a practice.
Maybe for you the parallel is going to the gym or practicing piano. Either way, it’s less about the end result and more to do with the progress in process.
If we view creativity as just that - a practice - it allows us to be more forgiving, more receptive to the ways that living a creative life can impact us personally.

We might be better positioned to see how creativity can change the texture of our lives, shape our worldviews, and push us to grow through continued conversation rather than a rush to the finish line.

I think you're both right. I don't think the team is overweighting the importance of engineering - that's really important when you have a cold start problem with a new social app. If you don't have volume, you need something else to create an edge and moat, in this case it's product experience... continuing below

There will likely be a point in the product's growth where bringing on someone / a team who can help build trust with high volumes of generalist users will make sense. 

That class of adopter won't care as much about the product, they'll be swayed by comms that make them feel something (fomo, companionship, etc) ..

That is the moment to kick into gear with a marketing person who can leverage data from existing and new users to build a brand that appeals and adopts the masses. The product is likely no longer central – the positioning is. 

Attempting that too early is also a mistake in lieu of an ace product, so keep building.

Clear founder led vision, comms, and marketing are always the strongest though, especially at this stage. 's thread feels relevant here:
https://twitter.com/jonwu_/status/1767702866985451787

The branding, partnerships, and general / data led marketing make more sense for legacy brands.

And honestly so much of web3 just rinses and repeats the same marketing/ partnerships/events without clear rationale as to how it supports business goals in the near term. It's expensive and often premature for startups, so big respect for the heads down approach.
